	<a href="https://calmatters.org/author/guest-commentary/" class="author">By Guest Commentary <img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/33ab0d2459dbbb6757d4c1275baa8bc8?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' class='avatar avatar-96 photo' height='96' width='96' /></a>	<span class="published">published: <time datetime="2020-04-15T05:25:00-07:00">April 15, 2020</time></span>
</div>
				<h2 class="largeheadline ">It’s time to protect California’s mountain lions</h2>
				<div class="featured-image">
	<div class="image">
		<img width="940" height="529" src="https://calmatters.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/04/mountain-lion.jpg?fit=940%2C529" class="attachment-large-wide-rec size-large-wide-rec wp-post-image" alt="mountain lion California" srcset="https://calmatters.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/04/mountain-lion.jpg?w=2048 2048w, https://calmatters.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/04/mountain-lion.jpg?w=300 300w, https://calmatters.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/04/mountain-lion.jpg?w=768 768w, https://calmatters.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/04/mountain-lion.jpg?w=1024 1024w, https://calmatters.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/04/mountain-lion.jpg?w=1536 1536w, https://calmatters.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/04/mountain-lion.jpg?w=460 460w, https://calmatters.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/04/mountain-lion.jpg?w=380 380w, https://calmatters.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/04/mountain-lion.jpg?w=780 780w, https://calmatters.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/04/mountain-lion.jpg?w=860 860w, https://calmatters.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/04/mountain-lion.jpg?w=940 940w" sizes="(max-width: 940px) 100vw, 940px" />	</div>
	<div class="imagebyline">
					<svg role="img" class="icon icon--camera" aria-label="camera"><use xlink:href="https://calmatters.org/wp-content/themes/thenewsproject/dist/svg/dist/symbol/svg/sprite.symbol.svg#camera"></use></svg>			<span>Scientists have shown that in some regions of California, mountain lions face an “extinction vortex” driven by roads and development that slice through their habitat and isolate populations. Photo courtesy of the National Park Service</span>
			</div>
</div>
			</div>

			
